dataIdInfo.idAbs: This dataset provides a representation of the watercourses within the Oregon portion of the Columbia basin as well as coastal and Great Basin watersheds. A selected subset of streams were originally derived from the Framework hydrography dataset and include all records originally present within the 1:100,000 scale PNW Hydrography dataset, named 1:24,000 scale streams and unnamed 1:24,000 scale streams where ODFW managed aquatic resource information exist. The data were migrated to events on NHD between 2012 and 2014. Whole stream route events were synchronized to April 2017 NHD geometry from April through June 2017.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The primary purpose of this dataset is to map the location of complete streams and rivers and to maintain a unique ID associated with "whole streams". It serves as a template for storing aquatic resource information as linear referenced events and publishing to a human readable format. This dataset is maintained as events on the National Hydrography Dataset (NHD) and is derived from April 2017 NHD geometry.

prcStep.stepDesc: Visually reviewed each subbasin-specific mixed scale hydrography dataset and where discontiguous watercourses (e.g. unnamed 24k stream with assoc. data) occurred, and where they could be connected using data from the source dataset, these features were added in to provide for contiguous watercourse features wherever possible in support of ODFW's data.

dataLineage.statement: This dataset originated from the 1:100,000 PNW River Reach files which were migrated to the Oregon Hydrography Framework dataset. From there, all other named, 1:24,000 scale Framework streams were added as were other stream features where ODFW had either fish habitat distribution or fish passage barrier information. In 2014, ODFW's mixed scale hydrography dataset was migrated to the NHD and is now referred to as the "Whole Stream Routes" dataset.

prcStep.stepDesc: Selected out features present in 1:100,000 scale PNW River Reach dataset (via the LLID field that was maintained across both datasets), all other named features at the 1:24,000 scale and unnamed 24,000 scale streams with associated fish habitat distribution or fish passage barrier data. The features were exported out to a separate "mixed scale hydrography" dataset.

Subset out features from the Oregon Hydrography water courses dataset into subbasin-specific datasets (e.g. Lower Columbia, Willamette, Deschutes, John Day, Umatilla and Walla Walla, Grande Ronde, Malheur and Owyhee)

Appended subbasin mixed scale hydrography datasets into a single, Oregon portion Columbia basin hydrography dataset. Analyzed for duplicate LLID's and merged routes where necessary to ensure 1 route / LLID. Added a field to track whether the feature is completely within Oregon, crosses a state border or is completely outside of the state. Populated the "instate" field.

Processed data to develop tributary (downstream) information and associate it with each water course feature. Ran the Feature Vertices to Points tool (start only option). to create a point at the downstream end of each water course route. Ran though process to ensure 1 start point / route. Used the Locate Features Along Routes tool to associate the start points back to the water course route features. Eliminated cases where the source route ID and output route ID were the same. Eliminated cases where measure values were equal to zero. Joined this output event table to the feature class table to populate the Tributary ID and measure information. The TribID field was then used to populate the trib name field.

Conducted frequency analyses on the LLID field and separately on the name field to identify necessary edits to each dataset. Merged water course features so that there is only one LLID / water course feature. Cleaned up headwater divergence issues where many headwaters either followed the incorrect path or multiple headwater reaches were named the same. Line source and edit info was tracked via two separate fields.

Whole Stream Route Migration to the NHD Metadata Process Steps
1. Subregion feature classes were created from ODFW’s statewide version of the LLID route-based, Oregon Framework Hydrography dataset. Based on HUC 3 or HUC4 polygons, lines were selected by Location/Intersect, and exported. 2. The subregion feature class attribute tables were then again exported, and measure and ID fields added to the new tables [WSR_LLID, FMeasure, TMeasure]. The route’s LLID was copied to the new ID field for preservation, and with the exception of the Klamath and Snake Rivers, the start/from measure was calculated to 0 and the end/to measure to the route’s length (shape length measured in kilometers). 3. NHD subregion flowlines and the subregion whole stream route table were added to a new ArcMap document. The ArcGIS “Transform Route Events” tool, with a tolerance of 3 feet, was used to transform route IDs and measures from the LLID-routed hydrography to the NHD. 4. Review of the route transformation event table looked for ReachCodes with a frequency greater than 1, records with measures that were not from 0 to 100, measure micro gaps within the same ReachCode that should be consolidated, and very small measures that indicate picking up a tributary by mistake due to search tolerance. 5. The transformed route event table was displayed on the NHD subregion flowlines and then exported to a new feature class. 6. The new subregion whole stream route feature classes, based on NHD geometry, were then used for import to a statewide HEM (Hydro Event Management) compliant feature class. The feature class ReachCodes and measures were used for HEM import, and the WSR_LLID field was linked to the Source_FeatureID field. 7. After HEM import, the HEM feature class was reviewed and manually edited, using four processes or checks, looking for: (1) geometry gaps and extraneous intersecting stubs, using the ArcGIS Data Reviewer multi-part line check with a routed feature class created from the HEM feature class on the whole stream route field [Source_FeatureID], (2) overlapping lines using topological validation, (3) significant differences in route length and location between the original and new hydrography datasets using the ArcGIS Symmetrical Difference tool, and (4) inclusion of all original routes. 8. LLID-based routes with no corresponding NHD flowline delineation, (no HEM features), were exported to a new feature class for use with NHD editing. Additionally, routes with a significant difference in verified location, or length, were added to this feature class and a comments field identified those records as needing flowline extensions or location modifications. When NHD flowline edits were complete, the whole stream route HEM feature class was manually edited to add, or update features. 9. Line features in ODFW’s statewide version of the LLID route-based, Oregon Framework Hydrography dataset, in general, have their end point (last vertex - red) upstream. This orientation transferred with HEM import. NHD flowlines have the last vertex at the downstream end. Digitizing by different LLID route editors, and HEM edits based on NHD flowlines, mixed line orientation in the HEM feature class. To orient routed features in the same direction: (1) A new routed feature class was created from the HEM feature class on the whole stream route field [Source_FeatureID]. (2) This feature class was dissected with the ArcGIS “Vertices to Points” tool to create start and end points for the route. (3) Elevation values were assigned to the start and end point features using ArcGIS Spatial Analyst “Extract Values to Points” tool and Digital Elevation Model datasets. (4) Features identified as flipped in relation to the whole, based on the elevation values, were exported to a new feature class for recalculation. (5) The selected and exported features (new feature class) were reoriented/ flipped, using the ArcGIS “Flip Line” tool. New start/from and end/to fields were added to the feature class attribute table, and calculated based on line (shape) length. (6) A new routed feature class was created using the ArcGIS “Create Routes” tool and the flipped features, based on the whole stream route field [Source_FeatureID]. (7) A “relate” was created between the original routed feature class (created in step 1), and the flipped features. Corresponding features were deleted from the original routed feature class and the flipped, routed features were then appended.
